    <content>&lt;b&gt;Management Science&lt;/b&gt; &lt;br&gt;We analyze statistical discrimination in hiring markets using a multiarmed bandit model. Myopic firms face workers arriving with heterogeneous observable characteristics. The association between the worker’s skill and characteristics is unknown ex ante; thus, firms need to learn it. Laissez-faire causes perpetual underestimation: minority workers are rarely hired, and therefore, the underestimation tends to persist. Even a marginal imbalance in the population ratio frequently results in perpetual underestimation. We demonstrate that a subsidy rule that is implemented as temporary affirmative action effectively alleviates discrimination stemming from insufficient data.This paper was accepted by Nicolas Stier-Moses, Special Issue on the Human-Algorithm Connection.Funding: This work was supported by the Social Sciences and Humanities Research Council of Canada [Grant 430-2020-00088] and JST ERATO [Grant JPMJER2301], Japan.Supplemental Material: The online appendix and data files are available at https://doi.org/10.1287/mnsc.2022.00893 .</content>
